The '''Internet Party''' ('''Partido de Internet''' in Spanish) is a political party founded in 2009 in Spain that tries to develop a [[liquid democracy]] system within the current legal system. The Internet Party has no ideology. They support an [[open list]] system where the elected members act representing the decisions taken by citizens in the Internet platform.{{citation needed|date=January 2011}}
During the [[Spanish general election, 2011|Spanish general election 2011]], the Internet Party presented 8 candidates in the electoral district of [[Cádiz (Spanish Congress Electoral District)|Cádiz]] and received 603 votes (0.09%).<ref>{{cite web|title=General Elections 2011 - Congress - Cadiz|url=http://www.generales2011.mir.es/99CG/DCG01119CI_L1.htm?d=0|publisher=Ministerio del Interior|accessdate=20 November 2011}}</ref>
